To create a TikZ diagram that visually demonstrates the consistency of saddle moves under mirror image, we can represent the saddle points and their reflections. Below is an example of how you might write the TikZ code to illustrate this concept:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
        % Define coordinates for the saddle points
        \coordinate (A) at (-1,0);
        \coordinate (B) at (1,0);

        % Draw the original saddle points
        \filldraw[blue] (A) circle[radius=0.05];
        \node[above left] at (A) {Saddle A};
        \filldraw[red] (B) circle[radius=0.05];
        \node[above right] at (B) {Saddle B};

        % Draw the mirror line (y-axis)
        \draw[dashed, thick] (0,-2) -- (0,2);

        % Reflect the saddle points across the y-axis
        \filldraw[green] (-A) circle[radius=0.05];
        \node[below left] at (-A) {Saddle A'};
        \filldraw[cyan] (-B) circle[radius=0.05];
        \node[below right] at (-B) {Saddle B'};

        % Connect the original and reflected points with dashed lines
        \draw[dashed, thick] (A) -- (-A);
        \draw[dashed, thick] (B) -- (-B);
    \end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{Consistency of Saddle Moves Under Mirror Image}
    \label{fig:saddle_mirror}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

This code creates a simple diagram with two blue and red dots representing the original saddle points. It then draws a dashed vertical line representing the mirror axis (the y-axis). The green and cyan dots represent the reflections of the original saddle points across this line. Dashed lines connect each original point to its reflection, demonstrating the consistency of the saddle moves under mirror image.

